apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 MOSCOW (AP) A strong earthquake jarred a large island off Russia's Pacific coast early Sunday, smashing furniture and sending frightened residents into the streets. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 There were no immediate reports of casualties or heavy damage. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The quake had a preliminary magnitude of 7.5, according to Russian seismological officials. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 It occurred at 1:03 am Sunday (9:03 a.m. EDT Saturday) near the sparsely populated northern tip of Sakhalin Island, eight time zones and some 4,000 miles east of Moscow. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Sakhalin Island, home to 750,000 people, is just north of the Japanese island of Hokkaido, on the Sea of Okhotsk. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 There were no immediate reports of damage on Hokkaido. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 No major damage was visible in one of the towns closest to the quake's epicenter, Okha, according to the district governor. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 But officials were worried about the fate of five nearby villages they could not reach by telephone. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 ``I have been living in this area for 42 years and it's the first earthquake of such force,'' Nayil Yarulin, governor of the Okhinsky district, said by telephone. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Local officials in Okha, a town of 35,000, found broken furniture and cracked walls inside many buildings. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Two aftershocks quickly followed the initial quake, Yarulin said. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The epicenter was located about 90 miles south of Okha and right along the coast, said Eduard Kozhukhov, a spokesman for Russia's Ministry for Emergency Situations in Moscow. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 U.S. and Japanese seismological officials made similar estimates, placing the preliminary magnitude at 7.6. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 A quake measuring magnitude 7 or greater is considered capable of widespread, heavy damage. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 But the epicenter was more than 400 miles north of the island's capital and major population center, Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Yarulin said officials on the southern end of the island reported no impact. 
